04391nam a22006735i 9781501743412DE-B159720191126113341.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||191126s2019    nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017434127 a10.7591/97815017434122doi  a(DE-B1597)534251  a(OCoLC)1129222787  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aHIS0130002bisacsh1 aHarari, Josue V., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aScenarios of the Imaginary :bTheorizing the French Enlightenment /cJosue V. Harari. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2019] 4c©1987  a1 online resource (240 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Nostalgia and Critical Theory -- t1. Transcoding -- t2. Eclectic Affinities: Imaginary/ Theory/ Reality -- t3. The Eunuch's Tale: Montesquieu's Imaginary of Despotism -- t4. Man Born of Man: Rousseau's Pedagogical Imaginary -- t5. Staging the Libertine Imaginary I: The Theoretical Scenario -- t6. Staging the Libertine Imaginary II: Personal and Fictional Scenarios -- t7. "You Are Requested to Close the Eyes": Out of the Barbershop, into the Academie Franchise -- tPostscript: Anguish -- tBibliography -- tName Index -- tSubject Index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFrom Proust to Beckett, from Blanchot to Derrida from Freud to Lacan, and from Lévi-Strauss to René Girard, all of our theories of modernity have been predicated upon a nostalgia for the real. In this lively and perceptive diagnosis of the malaise of contemporary theorists, Josué Harari interprets the French Enlightenment in terms of the relationship between theory and the imaginary, and explores the paradox by which theories that purport to describe the real lack any dimension of reality.Through readings of texts by some of the progenitors of influential modem theories, Harari explores the working strategies of the imaginary. In particular, he illuminates the founding moment, an instant of personal crisis for the author, during which a theory is infused by a fictional scenario: Montesquieu's "phantasm" of the body, resulting in his theory of government; Rousseau's narcissistic delirium in Emile, resulting in his theory of education; the theory of psychoanalysis, resulting from Freud's unconscious motives for choosing the Oedipal theory over the seduction theory of neurosis; and the theory of structural anthropology, generated by a psychodrama in Tristes Tropiques which Harari reads as a symptom of Lévi-Strauss's anguish when he is confronted with reality. Two striking chapters on Sade at the center of the book reveal the operation of the theoretical imaginary in libertine discourse.Scenarios of the Imaginary will find a wide audience among students and scholars of French literature, particularly of the eighteenth century, and of contemporary French thought, and among comparativists, literary theorists, anthropologists, and historians.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Nov 2019) 4aFrance. 4aWest European History. 7aHISTORY / Europe / France.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/9781501743412423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781501743412.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG